title: For Sale/Trade:  AR uppers and lowers: AAC, Spike's, PSA
postcontent:
One lower and sig brace sold!

One rifle, one pistol. Both lowers built from stripped receivers and assembled as pistols first, so you can legally swap both of them back and forth. Uppers are as-built unless otherwise noted.

Lowers: built by me on Spike's normal ie spider rollmark lowers. LPK was mil-spec PSA (the name brand PSA, not their lower level generic brand). They have the "cap screw through the grip hole threads" trigger mod, easily reversed if you desire. Ditto with the rear take down pin detent spring mod. Threading was factory from Spike's, so no half ass home tapping here. Both unfired  sad and with no to very minimal finish wear. I don't think either of them have any scratches, but I'll need to check before I can swear to it. Grip on both is a Blackhawk. They pass function tests with flying colors. One has a Magpul ASAP sling plate and MOE stock. The other has an A2 buffer tube with a Sig brace. Both with appropriate springs and buffers for their respective tubes.

Uppers: GI charging handles, AIM inside and out nitrided BCG (name brand not the unmarked and unwarrantied generic). One is  V1 one is V2. Bolt in both cases is MPI Carpenter 158. http://www.aimsurplus.com/product.aspx?item=XAIMBCGV2&name=AIM+v2+BLACK+NITRIDE+.223%2f5.56%2f.300+BLACKOUT+AR%2fM16+C158+Bolt+Carrier+Group&groupid=931&fprdct=1

PSA Premium 16'' 5.56mm 1:7 Carbine Length M4 Profile - Blemished 

AAC 9" .300 blackout upper, the same as here except for the BCG http://www.advanced-armament.com/300-BLK-Upper-9-Barrel_p_461.html Small scratch on the right side above the rear takedown pin. It's a tight fit on both the Spike's lowers, haven't tried it on any others. I have a Magpul AFG bolted to the bottom, directly to the smooth side of the URX. Had low rounds on it when I bought it, I was told <200 and I believe it. Haven't has a chance to fire it.  sad  sad 

If the .300 goes I also have... 5 or 6 boxes I think, of the Barnes 110 grain VOR-TX black tip ammo, generally considered one of if not the best supersonic anti-personnel load commercially available in this caliber. Loaded into mags but not cycled. Won't need it without the upper, so I can sell or include in the swap to even out value. Won't go if I still have the upper. http://www.midwayusa.com/product/430384/barnes-vor-tx-ammunition-300-aac-blackout-110-grain-tipped-tac-tx-bullet-flat-base-lead-free-box-of-20

$200 for the lower without buffer tube or stock. $350 for the PSA upper and $750 for the AAC upper, without BCG or CH.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Gen 3 - Glock 32 w/Crimson Lasergrips, extra's and additional mags - FS/FT
postcontent:
INTRO:

Hey there.  I'm a law abiding Texas citizen who has been on this site for a while and been through several trades.  Much like the rest of you, I enjoy trying out various firearms and have spent thousands of dollars in my pursuit of such.  Being that I'd like to stay married for a while longer I'm looking for like minded individuals who are honest, avoid games and take excellent care of their firearms.  I'm preferably looking for a trade and have a few guns up for consideration starting with the Glock in this ad.  Please keep reading for additional details and look for my other trade offers including - Stoeger Cougar 8000 9mm w/extras, Taurus PT145 Millennium Pro .45, HK P2000sk 9mm and Spikes Tactical AR w/several tasteful mods.  Unlike some - ALL of my stuff is always up for trade given the right circumstance (including my children ;-) although don't tell me wife please).

DESCRIPTION:

Firearm in question is a Glock 32.  I've owned this semi for about a year and a half only carrying it a few times otherwise used sparingly at the range.  This Glock is chambered in .40 with a stainless Wildcat barrel which is very nice addition over the stock .40 Glock barrel.  This Glock has Crimson Trace lasergrips on it and comes with both .40 and 357 mags, some spare .40 ammo (roughly 40 rounds) and locked soft carry case.  She shoots flawlessly and like most Glocks super accurate.  Crimson Trace lasergrips are obviously a nice addition and is dead on at about 15 yards.  I've put about 500 rounds total through this guy and like my other guns was immaculately maintained being cleaned and oiled after every single use.  Link for specs in the case anyone isn't aware:

http://us.glock.com/products/model/g32

TRADES:

I'm really looking for a nice SA/DA pistol in either .45 or 9mm being that most my other semi's are .40's.  I'd love to find another Kimber Pro/Ultra and willing to add cash or other valuables (your preference) to the trade.  I'm also interested in acquiring a shotgun as I don't have one at the moment and feeling a bit vulnerable for home defense.  All other compact 1911 frames will be considered.

All other trades will be considered as well so please send over any interests.  The worst either party can say is no and I have no problem field stripping to take additional pics for those interested however would just request you do the same if offering a firearm.

FAQ:

Why are you trading?  ~ Simple answer is I own two Glock 32's.  My primary has been heavily used for carry and at the range.  It also has sentimental value having acquired it through my late father.  Being I have two and want the option of adding to my collection versus spending the money it makes the most sense to part with at the moment.

Where are you willing to travel?  ~ I'm in the Lake Worth area however willing to travel 20-30 min for the right trade.  If an even trade I'd only ask that you meet me half way which seems fair.  If the trade is a little more or less I'm willing to travel further or shorter to accommodate.  Time is money and money is time.  Please be fair with both.

Trade requirements?  ~ I only ask for a bill of sale, F2F meeting and current TX DL or CHL.  This follows law and it is important that I do so as well.

Any other questions please don't hesitate to contact me.

title: For Sale:  NEW Ruger Redhawk 44MAG Stainless 5.5" Wood Grips
postcontent:
Forget those other sissy guns, this is a REAL gun.  The Ruger Redhawk 44MAG Stainless 6-Shot Revolver, with 5.5" barrel, red wood grips, bladed front sight, box and paperwork.  This gun is fresh from the factory and is perfect for hunting season.  Here is a great description from Champion Firearms:

"Since its introduction in 1979, the Ruger Redhawk has proven to be a rugged, reliable, accurate and very strong sixgun. As a rule of thumb, Ruger's double action revolvers like the Redhawk have heavier frames and thicker chamber walls than the competition. They are built for years of hard use and will never wear out. The design is a solid frame and the massive cylinder locks up in front at the crane and at the rear into the recoil plate of the heavy frame. The ejector rod does not rotate, and will never unscrew itself from its fixed position, locking up the cylinder, as happens too frequently with some other double-action revolvers. The cylinder bolt notches are cut a bit off center, making a stronger cylinder wall than on designs that place this cut directly over the center of each chamber.

The investment cast frame of the Ruger Redhawk has no removable side plate; most of the internal parts are attached to the trigger guard assembly, which is removed from the bottom of the frame. Most revolvers on the market are built on a removable side plate design that is over one hundred years old. They were built to handle low pressure cartridges of the period. When .44 magnum cartridges came along in the '50s, the old designs were just made larger to handle the extra intensity of firing magnums. Still, magnum revolvers built on the removable side plate design tend to loosen with heavy use. Ruger’s double action revolvers like the Redhawk have always been built without a removable side plate. This adds needed strength to the frame around the cylinder.

The Ruger Redhawk comes equipped with adjustable sights and hardwood grips. The hammer spur is checkered for a secure hold while cocking the piece for single action fire, and the firing pin is protected from accidental discharge by Ruger’s famous and proven transfer bar safety system. This makes it nearly impossible for the gun to "go off" when dropped. When the hammer is fully forward, it rests on the frame and cannot contact the firing pin. The transfer bar itself rises as the trigger is pulled. Then when a cocked hammer falls, it hits the transfer bar (thus "transferring" the energy to the firing pin) which subsequently fires the shot. Loaded and unloading is easily accomplished by pressing in on the button mounted in the frame's left recoil shield, which subsequently swings the cylinder out. This heavy duty workhorse features a solid stainless steel construction, and includes a 5.5" barrel. The action is driven by a traditional double / single design and unlike other revolvers, Ruger exclusively uses higher quality music wire springs."
